spec: ab3331
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__, __ior__, __ixor__ dict-presence (in-place &=, |=, ^=) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__iand__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __iand__. In-place bitwise AND (__iand__, &=) is the augmented assignment variant of __and__. abc types define no __and__ (confirmed false in wave 661), so __iand__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no bitwise or numeric semantics — ABC &= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve in-place bitwise AND. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __iand__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not bitwise types. f &= n is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__ior__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ior__. In-place bitwise OR (__ior__, |=) is the augmented assignment variant of __or__. abc types define no __or__ (confirmed false in wave 661), so __ior__ is equally absent. Note: Python 3.9 introduced __ior__ on the built-in dict type for in-place merging, but abc types are abstract base class machinery — not dict-like types. abc.ABC has no bitwise or dict-merge data model; ABC |= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; in-place bitwise OR is entirely absent. The function type does not define __ior__; f |= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "Key finding (__ixor__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ixor__. In-place bitwise XOR (__ixor__, ^=) is the augmented assignment variant of __xor__. abc types define no __xor__ (confirmed false in wave 661), so __ixor__ is equally absent. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no bitwise or integer data model; ABC ^= n is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; ^= has no meaning for metaclass objects. The function type does not define __ixor__; f ^= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 668 (__ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place augmented assignment dunder tested across 18 consecutive waves (652–669). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __iand__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__iand__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __iand__.
# In-place bitwise AND (__iand__, &=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __and__. abc types define no __and__ (wave 661), so __iand__ is
#   equally absent.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no bitwise
#   or numeric semantics. ABC &= n is not a defined Python expression; ABC
#   has no __iand__ to serve as an implementation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. In-place bitwise AND has no role in ABCMeta's
#   responsibilities (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __iand__. f &= n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no
#   bitwise or in-place augmented assignment data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3331.iand:
  description: "abc types __iand__ dict-presence checks; wave 669"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3331

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3331001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__iand__"], false]
    - ["ab3331002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__iand__"], false]
    - ["ab3331003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__iand__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ior__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ior__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ior__.
# In-place bitwise OR (__ior__, |=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __or__. abc types define no __or__ (wave 661), so __ior__ is
#   equally absent.
# Note: Python 3.9 introduced __ior__ on the built-in dict type for
#   in-place dict merging (d |= other). abc types are abstract base class
#   machinery — not dict-like types. This dict-specific __ior__ is entirely
#   irrelevant to abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, or the function type.
# abc.ABC: no bitwise or dict-merge data model; ABC |= n is not a defined
#   Python expression. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no
#   state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __ior__ for in-place bitwise OR. ABCMeta's
#   API surface (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no
#   arithmetic, bitwise, or augmented assignment component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ior__. f |= n is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to its role
#   as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3331.ior:
  description: "abc types __ior__ dict-presence checks; wave 669"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3331

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3331004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ior__"], false]
    - ["ab3331005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ior__"], false]
    - ["ab3331006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ior__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ixor__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ixor__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ixor__.
# In-place bitwise XOR (__ixor__, ^=) is the augmented assignment variant
#   of __xor__. abc types define no __xor__ (wave 661), so __ixor__ is
#   equally absent.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper with no bitwise or integer
#   data model. ABC ^= n is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-
#   hierarchy machinery — not in operator overloading. ABCMeta ^= n is not
#   a valid Python expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ixor__. Unlike sets, which use __ixor__ for
#   in-place symmetric difference, CPython's built-in function type has no
#   __ixor__. f ^= n is not a valid Python expression for callable objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3331.ixor:
  description: "abc types __ixor__ dict-presence checks; wave 669"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3331

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
